h3. Issue Summary

If you have a custom group created on your Site Administration, like _Avangers_, for example, and go to your Confluence instance to add this group with analytics permissions, it won't take effect, because of this group is full lower case in the analytics permissions list.
h3. Environment
 * Confluence Cloud Premium

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a group called as _Avengers_;
 # Add a testing user to this group;
 # Go to your Confluence instance;
 # Go to *Settings > Analytics Permissions*;
 # Click on the *Edit Permissions* button;
 # Add the _Avengers_ group with the *Use Analytics* permission - note it is set as _avengers_ (with the *A* in lower case);
 # Impersonate the testing user and try to use the analytics feature.

h3. Expected Results

You are able to access the analytics feature
h3. Actual Results

You are not able to access it, because your group name is different.
h3. Workaround

Create a new group with full lower case letters and add this group with the analytics permission

h3. Summary
Feature request raised in Developer Support: https://ecosystem.atlassian.net/browse/DEVHELP-3131

It would be helpful to have the ability to open a custom macro editor dialog without chrome.

In this way app developers could have more freedom in the design of the macro editor.

For example at the moment we are facing the following issue (see https://recordit.co/vqRO46YFQ2 ):1) the header and footer of the editor is not aligned with the latest ADG.2) the position of secondary button (after the "Cancel") is not ideal 

{code}
"dynamicContentMacros": [
....
{
"editor": 
    {
        "url": "/bw-atlassian/confluence/macro-editor.htm",
        "editTitle": {"value": "Edit Balsamiq Wireframes"},
        "insertTitle": {"value": "Add Balsamiq Wireframes"},
        "width": "865px","height": "350px",
        "chrome": false  // NEW FEATURE: no chrome
    }
}
{code}

